<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Sub-Zero authorized service</p>
    <h2>The LA premium refrigerator standard. Independent Bakke family since 1945.</h2>

    <p>Sub-Zero is the LA premium refrigerator standard. The Sub-Zero Group is one of the few American appliance manufacturers still independent and family-owned: the Bakke family, three generations, since 1945, Madison Wisconsin. While most appliance brands have been acquired by private equity or industrial conglomerates, Sub-Zero has stayed independent. This is reflected in the build quality, the service network commitment, and the lifetime cabinet warranty that no other brand matches.</p>

    <p>Our techs service Sub-Zero across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, Riverside. Beverly Hills, Bel Air, Hidden Hills, Pacific Palisades, and Malibu have concentrated Sub-Zero installations because the brand defines premium kitchen architecture in those neighborhoods. We are part of the <strong>Sub-Zero authorized service network</strong>, which is critical for warranty preservation and proper Sub-Zero service procedures. General appliance handymen working on Sub-Zero often violate warranty terms or use incorrect parts.</p>

    <p>The full Sub-Zero refrigeration lineup we service: <strong>BI Built-In Series</strong> (BI-30, BI-36, BI-42, BI-48 plus R/F variants), the flagship built-in line. <strong>700-Series columns</strong> (700TC, 700TR, 700TF, 700TFI standalone freezer column, 736TR, 736TFI), current generation built-in. <strong>648PROG and PROG variants</strong>, pro-style with glass doors. <strong>Designer Series (DS-3650RFI)</strong>, newer design language with panel-ready options. <strong>Classic PRO Series (PRO-4250G)</strong>. <strong>Integrated Series (IT-30R, IT-30CIID)</strong>, fully integrated panel-ready. <strong>Refrigerator drawers</strong> (UC series plus 700-Series UC).</p>

    <p>$89 residential diagnostic, waived with repair. BHGS #A49573. EPA 608 Universal certified for R-22 legacy and R-134a sealed-system work. R-600a awareness for newer post-2020 Sub-Zero hydrocarbon refrigerant models. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 LINEUP -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">Lineup and architecture</p>
    <h2>Sub-Zero lineup and what fails on each.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Six product lines, one engineering signature: the dual refrigeration system. Separate compressors and evaporators for refrigerator and freezer compartments. The single biggest reliability advantage Sub-Zero has over competitors using single-evaporator designs.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">BI Built-In Series (Flagship)</h3>
    <p>The most common Sub-Zero installations in LA premium homes. BI-30 (30 inch all-refrigerator), BI-36 (36 inch refrigerator + freezer), BI-42 (42 inch refrigerator + freezer, the most popular Sub-Zero size), BI-48 (48 inch largest standard built-in). Plus R-only and F-only variants for kitchen designs with separate refrigerator and freezer columns.</p>

    <p>The <strong>dual refrigeration system</strong> is the Sub-Zero engineering signature. Separate evaporators for fridge and freezer compartments. Most other brands use single evaporator with damper transfer, so one common failure mode disables both compartments. Sub-Zero's dual-evap means fridge and freezer fail independently and are much more reliable.</p>

    <p>Common BI-Series failures by year:</p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Year 6 to 10:</strong> door gasket compression. Sub-Zero gaskets last longer than industry standard but eventually wear. Replacement $260 to $440.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 8 to 12:</strong> condenser fan motor (one of the dual evaporators, typically refrigerator side first due to higher cycle frequency).</li>
      <li><strong>Year 10 to 14:</strong> defrost board failure on freezer side.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 12 to 16:</strong> refrigerant slow leak (rare on Sub-Zero, copper construction quality means leaks are uncommon, but happen at fittings or evaporator brazed joints).</li>
      <li><strong>Year 15 to 20:</strong> compressor mechanical wear, one or both compressors. Replace-vs-repair conversation kicks in here.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 20+:</strong> multiple component cascading replacement, but the cabinet typically still excellent.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="series-h3">700-Series Columns (Current Generation)</h3>
    <p>Updated built-in design with separate refrigerator and freezer columns. 700TC (30 inch refrigerator), 700TR (36 inch refrigerator), 700TF (30 inch freezer column part of combination), 700TFI (standalone freezer column 30 inch), 736TR (36 inch all-refrigerator variant), 736TFI (36 inch freezer column). Same dual refrigeration system architecture as BI-Series. 700-Series uses updated electronic control boards with diagnostic codes available.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Pro Series (648PROG, PROG variants)</h3>
    <p>Pro-style restaurant-positioned. 648PROG = 48 inch with stainless steel and glass door display. Common in LA premium kitchens designed for professional cooking aesthetics. Same dual refrigeration internals. Glass door anti-condensation heater system adds a service item: typical year 8 to 12 glass heater wire replacement.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Designer Series (DS-3650RFI)</h3>
    <p>Newer 2020+ design language. Panel-ready French door (DS-3650RFI = 36 inch 50/50 French door). Updated electronic control system. Newer Sub-Zero models with R-600a refrigerant transition possible, requires R-600a awareness for service.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Integrated Series (IT-30R, IT-30CIID)</h3>
    <p>Fully integrated panel-ready Sub-Zero. IT-30R = 30 inch all-refrigerator with custom panel mounting. IT-30CIID = 30 inch combination panel-ready. Common in high-end Beverly Hills and Hidden Hills full integrated kitchens where no appliance is visible (everything panel-mounted matching cabinetry).</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Classic PRO Series (PRO-4250G)</h3>
    <p>Classic Sub-Zero design language. PRO-4250G = 42 inch pro classic with glass door display. Older but actively serviced. Sub-Zero parts availability extends beyond most other brands.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Refrigerator Drawers (UC / 700-Series UC)</h3>
    <p>Under-counter Sub-Zero drawer refrigeration. Kitchen islands, butler's pantries, master bedrooms. UC-24R (24 inch refrigerator drawer), UC-24F (freezer drawer). Different service profile than full-size: drawer slide service items, drawer-specific gaskets.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 TYPICAL SCENARIOS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Common scenarios</p>
    <h2>Top Sub-Zero repairs in our 5-county territory.</h2>

    <p>In rough order of frequency on Sub-Zero service calls:</p>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Door gasket replacement.</strong> Sub-Zero gaskets compress eventually (year 6 to 10 inland, 5 to 8 coastal). Replacement straightforward with Sub-Zero OEM gasket.</li>
      <li><strong>Condenser fan motor (one of dual system).</strong> Typical year 8 to 12 failure on refrigerator side first. Sub-Zero OEM via authorized service network.</li>
      <li><strong>Defrost system board.</strong> Modern Sub-Zero electronic defrost board. Year 10 to 14 typical replacement.</li>
      <li><strong>Glass door anti-condensation heater (PROG and PRO-G models).</strong> Heater wire in door frame fails year 8 to 12. Replacement requires partial frame disassembly.</li>
      <li><strong>Refrigerant leak repair.</strong> Rare on Sub-Zero copper construction but happens. EPA 608 leak repair with proper procedures, R-600a awareness for newer models.</li>
      <li><strong>Damper actuator.</strong> Less common on Sub-Zero (the dual-evaporator design avoids the damper failure mode of single-evap brands), but happens on some configurations.</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor replacement (year 15 to 20).</strong> Significant repair but Sub-Zero cabinets routinely outlast 2 to 3 component generations. Replace-vs-repair math almost always favors repair.</li>
      <li><strong>Drawer slide service (UC drawer models).</strong> Drawer-specific wear at year 6 to 10.</li>
      <li><strong>Authorized warranty processing.</strong> For warranty-eligible repairs, we coordinate through the Sub-Zero authorized service network for proper documentation.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 REAL REPAIR STORIES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">Real repairs</p>
    <h2>Composite stories from the route.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Five Sub-Zero jobs from the past 90 days. Models, symptoms, diagnosis, parts, time, total. Names omitted; the technical scenarios are typical of what we see weekly.</p>

    <div class="story-grid">
      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Bel Air, Sub-Zero 736TR built-in 36-inch all-refrigerator, 13 years old, R-134a.</h3>
        <p>Temp drift, food at 44 to 46°F instead of 38°F. Diagnostic: condenser fan motor seizing intermittently (heat-cycle related at 13 years). Cleaned condenser coils, replaced fan motor with Sub-Zero OEM via authorized network. Total: $89 plus $445 motor plus $290 labor = $824. 13-year service interval typical for this component on Sub-Zero.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Beverly Hills, Sub-Zero BI-42S/S 42-inch built-in refrigerator + freezer, 11 years old, R-134a.</h3>
        <p>Refrigerator side warming (38°F climbed to 48°F), freezer side normal at -5°F. Diagnostic: refrigerator-side condenser fan motor end-of-life. This is the dual refrigeration system reliability advantage in action: fridge-side failure independent of freezer side. Replaced fridge-side fan motor only. Total: $89 plus $390 motor plus $290 labor = $769. 11-year repair on a $14,000 built-in: economic math obvious.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Pacific Palisades, Sub-Zero 648PROG 48-inch pro-style with glass door, 18 years old, R-134a.</h3>
        <p>Multiple cascading issues. Door gasket compressed flat, condenser fan motor (refrigerator side) bearings shot, ice maker module end-of-life, glass door anti-condensation heater wire open-circuited. Owner asked replace-vs-repair. Replacement Sub-Zero Pro 48 inch = $24,000+ plus custom cabinet adjustments = $30,000+ total. Repair quote $1,800. Approved repair, all 4 components replaced in single visit. Sub-Zero now ready for another 5 to 7 years easily. Total: $89 plus $1,180 parts plus $830 labor = $2,099.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Hidden Hills, Sub-Zero IT-30CIID 30-inch integrated combination, 7 years old, R-134a.</h3>
        <p>Fridge warm, freezer cold. Classic damper failure pattern (less common on Sub-Zero but happens on some configurations). Diagnosed and replaced damper actuator. Total: $89 plus $290 part plus $180 labor = $559. Integrated panel-mount Sub-Zero serviced without panel damage during access.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Malibu, Sub-Zero DS-3650RFI 36-inch Designer Series French door panel-ready, 4 years old, R-600a.</h3>
        <p>Newer Sub-Zero with R-600a hydrocarbon refrigerant. Refrigerant slow leak. R-600a awareness and proper procedures required (R-600a is flammable, EPA 608 plus R-600a handling protocols differ from R-134a). Brazed leak repair, evacuated, recharged R-600a per spec. Total: $89 plus $580 refrigerant plus $720 labor plus leak detection = $1,389.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 HONEST SCOPE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Scope</p>
    <h2>What we do for Sub-Zero, and what we don't.</h2>

    <p><strong>We service:</strong></p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>Full BI Built-In Series (BI-30, BI-36, BI-42, BI-48 plus R/F variants)</li>
      <li>700-Series columns (700TC, 700TR, 700TF, 700TFI, 736TR, 736TFI)</li>
      <li>Pro Series (648PROG, PROG variants)</li>
      <li>Designer Series (DS-3650RFI)</li>
